==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Ton
<hw>Ton</hw> <pr>(t⟦ucr⟧n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>tonne</ets>, <ets>tunne</ets>, a tun, <er>AS</er>. <ets>tunne</ets>
a tun, tub, a large vessel; akin to G. & F. <ets>tonne</ets> a ton, tun,
LL. <ets>tunna</ets> a tun; all perhaps of Celtic origin; cf. Ir. &
Gael. <ets>tunna</ets> a tun. Cf. <er>Tun</er>,<er>Tunnel</er>.]</ety>
<fld>(Com.)</fld> <def>A measure of weight or quantity.</def>
Specifically: --⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(a)</sd> <def>The weight of twenty hundredweight.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ In England, the <xex>ton</xex> is 2,240 pounds. In the
United States the ton is commonly estimated at 2,000 pounds, this being
sometimes called the <xex>short ton</xex>, while that of 2,240 pounds is
called the <xex>long ton</xex>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(b)</sd> <fld>(Naut. & Com.)</fld> <def>Forty cubic feet of
space, being the unit of measurement of the burden, or carrying
capacity, of a vessel; as a vessel of 300 <xex>tons</xex> burden.</def>
See the Note under <er>Tonnage</er>.⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(c)</sd> <fld>(Naut. & Com.)</fld> <def>A certain weight or
quantity of merchandise, with reference to transportation as freight;
as, six hundred weight of ship bread in casks, seven hundred weight in
bags, eight hundred weight in bulk; ten bushels of potatoes; eight
sacks, or ten barrels, of flour; forty cubic feet of rough, or fifty
cubic feet of hewn, timber, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Ton</xex> and <xex>tun</xex> have the same
etymology, and were formerly used interchangeably; but now
<xex>ton</xex> generally designates the weight, and <xex>tun</xex> the
cask. See <er>Tun</er>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tonality</ent>⟦br⟧
